@NODE "introduction" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Introduction"

A music manager for AmigaOS

This project started out as the GUI for a project I was working on, an MP3 jukebox based on an A1200 fitted out with a MAS Player. Originally I had planned on having a very minimal GUI, the main control and display being done through the front panel of the jukebox hardware. The player itself was to have a simple LCD display and CD player-like controls, and an iPod-style menu system.

However, during development the application grew more and more features and ended up with an ugly but functional GadTools interface which works well on a native PAL screen - just perfect for putting under the TV! It also occurred to me that software that manages your music library in a fashion like iTunes and the iPod doesn't actually exist on the Amiga, so I thought my GUI could fill this void for low-end machines with MAS players. I also decided that I would add a nice GUI and plenty more advanced features (like encoding CDs, CDDB access etc.) for those users with high-end Amigas.

Since version 0.5, the source has been forked to two separate projects - the "Jukebox edition" which is what you have here for low-end Amigas, and the normal edition which will be released as a separate application for high-end Amigas.

AmiTunes is, and will be free, though I wouldn't say no to donations :) Way too
early to be thinking of things like that though!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "disclaimer" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Disclaimer"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition Disclaimer

This is beta software, it will crash under certain circumstances, it does funny things and I can't be held responsible for any lost data or hardware. Having said that, it has reasonable error checking and will usually just give an error message and quit if something goes wrong.

AmiTunes has the ability to modify your files, and though it's been well tested, I can't guarantee there aren't any nasty bugs which might destroy your data. Use it at your own risk.

Also, there is the option to attach extra hardware to your Amiga. Of course this can destroy your Amiga if you're not careful, or just plain unlucky. Make sure you know what you're doing before you attach anything to your computer!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "operation" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - How It Works"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition Overview

The aim of AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition is to catalogue and organise all the MP3s you have stored on your Amiga's hard drive. It's primarily aimed at low-end Amigas using a MAS player, but can be used on higher end Amigas too (and indeed it works fine on my own AmigaOne XE-G4). It doesn't actually decode the MP3s itself, but simply passes them over to a @{"decoding engine" Link "engines"} to produce the sound. These engines can be either software or hardware based, and are quite basic in nature.

AmiTunes keeps track of any MP3 files it has been given in a central library file which contains all the relevant information about the MP3s. Normally the library would be loaded automatically when AmiTunes starts, and saved when it quits, but this is user configurable. AmiTunes presents the library similarly to Apple's iTunes (specifically its "Browse" pane), giving the user a list of artist, albums and songs which are dynamically updated based on user choices in other lists. It also supports multiple playlists which can be edited as desired by the user, and a special @{"shuffle" Link "shuffle"} playlist which shows a number of upcoming songs chosen at random. The library is searchable, with the search results being added to a "search results" playlist.

AmiTunes can, if desired, also organise your files for you based on their ID3 tag information in the format <AmiTunes Library Directory>/<Artist>/<Album>/<filename>.mp3, updating it automatically as you edit the information associated with each file. ID3 tags are read to organise the library, and can optionally be written back to the file when edited. Songs can be added by drag 'n' drop from Workbench, and AmiTunes can either copy these files into the library directory, or use them from their original location.

As AmiTunes started out life as a simple library manager for my custom jukebox project, it supports an RS-232 LCD terminal display for track names etc., and for browse and operation menus, which can be controlled via custom input hardware on a classic Amiga.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "requirements" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Requirements"

What you'll need to run AmiTunes Jukebox edition:

   - An Amiga (obviously!)
   - OS 3.0+ (it might work under 2.05 but this HAS NOT BEEN TESTED!)
   - A FULL OS install - AmiTunes depends on some OS files being in their correct location
   - An FPU (for the moment, until I figure out how to remove the dependency on it...)
   - The power to decode MP3s, be it a fast processor or a MAS player
   - id3tag.library (Get it from AmiNet - util/libs/id3tag_lib.lha)
   - reqtools.library (Also from AmiNet - util/libs/ReqToolsLib.lha)
   - RexxMast running
   - Screenmode of at least 640x256
   - Jeez, I can't remember what else!


Optionally, you might like these:

   - More than one MP3 (it'll work with one or none, but why bother?)
   - A MAS-Player for decoding MP3s on a classic machine
   - AmigaAmp (AmiNet - mus/play/AmigaAMP.lha) if you want to use it for your software decoding
   - AHI if you want to use the included software decoding engine
   - A serial alphanumeric LCD panel (from Crystalfontz.com or similar)
   - Some custom hardware to provide front-panel buttons (Classic Amigas only)


AmiTunes Jukebox Edition has not been tested on any Amiga clones (MorphOS, AROS etc.) but in theory it should work if using the software decoding engines. If anyone has tried it under a clone OS, please let me know if it works!
@ENDNODE
@NODE "installation" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Installation"

To install AmiTunes Jukebox Edition, simply drag the directory to wherever you like on your hard drive and it'll be happy there. Please be aware however that it needs to write to files in its program directory to work correctly.

You will need to set some settings for AmiTunes to work correctly once installed. The first time you run AmiTunes, it will probably complain about not being able to find preference or library files. You can ignore these for now, but you should set your @{"preferences" Link "preferences"} and save them before you use AmiTunes for the first time. The main setting is the Library/Music path. @{b}This path must be correctly set for AmiTumes to work correctly!@{ub} This is where you want AmiTunes to store its library file, and if you want, the actual music files it manages. The default setting is to Music:AmiTunes/ so if your music is all stored on a Music: partition, simply create an AmiTunes directory there and you're done!

@{b}IMPORTANT!@{ub} I strongly recommend reviewing all the @{"settings" Link "preferences"} before you use AmiTunes with your MP3 collection however, as it does have the capability to move your files around, rename them and edit their id3 tags, so you should decide in advance how many or few of these features you would like to use. Engine settings should also be set before use, as without this setting, you won't hear anything!!


@ENDNODE
@NODE "usage" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Usage"

Usage of AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition

@{b}IMPORTANT!@{ub} I strongly recommend reviewing all the @{"settings" Link "preferences"} before you use AmiTunes with your MP3 collection, as it does have the capability to move your files around, rename them and edit their id3 tags. You should decide in advance how many or few of these features you would like to use and set the preferences accordingly.

Since the usage is quite detailed, I've arranged it into the following subsections:

   @{" Starting up   " Link "startup"}  Starting up AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition

   @{" Main Window   " Link "mainwindow"}  The main AmiTunes window

   @{" Program Menus " Link "menus"}  The menus of the main AmiTunes window

   @{" Preferences   " Link "preferences"}  Configuring AmiTunes

   @{" Adding Music  " LINK "addmusic"}  Adding MP3 files to your AmiTunes library

   @{" View Modes    " Link "viewmodes"}  Using the Browse or Playlist viewing modes

   @{" Shuffle       " Link "shuffle"}  Using the special "Shuffle" playlist

   @{" ARexx         " Link "arexx"}  Controlling AmiTunes via ARexx

   @{" Engines       " Link "engines"}  AmiTunes' decoding engines

   @{" Jukebox       " LINK "jukebox"}  Using AmiTunes as a jukebox

   @{" Keyboard      " LINK "keyboard"}  Controlling AmiTunes with the keyboard

   @{" LCD Menus     " LINK "lcdmenus"}  Using the LCD menus to control AmiTunes

   @{" Program Files " LINK "files"}  @{i}(Advanced)@{ui} A description of the files used by AmiTunes

@ENDNODE

@NODE "startup" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Start Up"

Starting AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition

Nothing special is required for starting AmiTunes. No tooltypes are used, simply double click the icon in Workbench and it will start up. AmiTunes will look for a preferences file in its PROGDIR:; if it doesn't exist you'll get a warning which can be ignored, and AmiTunes will use safe default settings. Choose Save in the Options window to create a preferences file if one does not exist. Depending on the user settings, AmiTunes will also look for its library file in the AmiTunes Library directory, and will give a warning if it doesn't exist. Choose "Save Library" from the Project menu to create a new library file - though you must have at least one MP3 in the library to save it.

AmiTunes can also be started from the shell, and accepts one argument: debug. Starting AmiTunes with the debug argument will produce lots of debug output, which might help you troubleshoot, but probably makes more sense to me! If you're having trouble with AmiTunes and need my help, the debug output can help me greatly to understand the problem.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "mainwindow" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Main Window"

The AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition Main Window

When AmiTunes starts, the main window will open, showing the main controls across the top of the window, three listviews in the middle of the window, and three text gadgets across the bottom, one below each listview. Before any music is added the listviews will be empty, but once music is added to the library, the listviews will be populated with the artists, albums and tracks of the songs in your library. The main features of this window are as follows:

   @{b}- Play/Pause/Stop/Skip Back/Skip Forward@{ub}
Pretty much self explanatory, but see the @{"Jukebox" Link "jukebox"} section for a detailed description.

   @{b}- Repeat Off/One/All@{ub}
Cycles between the repeat modes - Off (don't repeat), One (repeat the current track) and All (repeat the current songlist).

   @{b}- Browser/Playlists@{ub}
Switches the view mode between Browser and Playlists mode. See @{"View Modes" Link "viewmodes"} for more information on the different view modes.

   @{b}- Search@{ub}
Type some characters in here and press enter to search the library for any matches. Will search for the entire search text in song titles, artist names, album titles and genres. Search results are listed in a special playlist called "Search Results" which will be shown automatically, and will remain in this playlist until another search is carried out.

   @{b}- Time Slider@{ub}
This shows the current position in the playback of the current song. The time elapsed is also displayed to the left, and the track length to the right of the slider. Drag the slider to skip to that position in the current track. Has no effect when stopped.

   @{b}- Artists Listview@{ub}
This listview will display every unique artist in your library, along with a special item at the top of the list which looks something like "<<All N Artists>>", where N is the number of unique artists in your library. Clicking on an artist's name will cause the Albums and Songs listviews to automatically update and filter to show only albums and tracks by the selected artist. Choosing the "<<All N Artists>>" item at the top will cause the Albums and Songs listviews to show all available entries and not filtered by a particular artist.

   @{b}- Albums Listview@{ub}
This listview will list all the unique albums in your library, or associated with a particular artist if one is selected in the Artists listview. Clicking on an album title will cause the Songs listview to update and filter, showing only songs associated with the selected album. Again, clicking the "<<All N Albums>>" will cause the Songs listview to list all songs associated with all albums in the Albums listview.

   @{b}- Songs Listview@{ub}
This listview will list all the songs relevant to the current selections in the Artists and Albums listviews (see above), and determines which tracks will be played and in what sequence. Selecting a song allows certain actions to be carried out on it (see @{"Program Menu Items" Link "menus"} for details). If a song is selected that isn't playing, and the currently playing track finishes or Play is pressed, the selected track will be played. If the selected song is playing, and it finishes, the selection will be moved to the next track. Double-clicking on a song title causes that song to be played straight away.

   @{b}- Selection Text Gadgets@{ub}
Below the three listviews, one text gadget each corresponds to the Artists, Albums and Songs list. When an item is clicked in any list, the relevant text gadget is updated to contain the name of that item. Editing the contents of the text gadget and pressing Enter will update the relevant details in the library, and if "Automatically sort AmiTunes library drawer" is enabled in the @{"Preferences" Link "preferences"}, AmiTunes will also update all the relevant files' ID3 tags. Note that all relevant tracks will be automatically updated in the case of album or artist modification, not just the currently selected track. This enables easy renaming of an entire artist or album in one go. The @{"Song->Information..." link "menus"} menu item can be used to update the artist and album details of a single track.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "menus" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Program Menus"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition Program Menus

The main window uses some menus for controlling AmiTunes. Four main menus are provided - Project, song, Playlist and Options. The menu items function as follows:

   @{b}- Project->Import Song...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga S)
Presents a file requester which can be used to select a single MP3 file which will be added to the library and, depending on @{"settings" Link "preferences"}, copies to the AmiTunes library drawer. See @{"Adding Music" Link "addmusic"} for more information.

   @{b}- Project->Import Drawer...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga D)
Presents a file requester which can be used to select a drawer which will be searched for MP3 files to be added to the library and, depending on @{"settings" Link "preferences"}, copied to the AmiTunes library drawer. See @{"Adding Music" Link "addmusic"} for more information.

   @{b}- Project->Load Library@{ub}
Loads the main AmiTunes library from the library drawer specified in the preferences, replacing any currently loaded library and playlists. Once loaded, the main window will be updated and the Artists and Albums lists sorted into alphabetical order.

   @{b}- Project->Save Library@{ub}
Saves the current library and playlists to the AmiTunes library drawer, replacing any previous version of the library stored in that drawer. The library should be saved whenever any music is added, removed or has its information changed so that the information is updated the next time you use AmiTunes. The library can be saved automatically when AmiTunes quits by enabling the option in the preferences.

   @{b}- Project->About...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga ?)
Opens a requester displaying version information etc.

   @{b}- Project->About...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga Q)
Quits AmiTunes, saving the library if the setting is enabled. If not, and Jukebox mode is disabled, AmiTunes will warn you about any unsaved changes to the library. If Jukebox mode is enabled, AmiTunes will quit regardless of unsaved changes!

   @{b}- Song->Information...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga I)
Opens an information window for the selected song, containing information from the ID3 tags, along with location, length of track, play count and rating. Most of these attributes can be modified - clicking Save will save the changes to the library, and if the setting is enabled, to the ID3 tags of the file. Cancel closes the window without saving changes. Previous and Next show the information of the previous and next tracks in the current song list.

   @{b}- Song->Play@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga P)
Starts the selected song playing if it is not already playing. Cancels pause if paused.

   @{b}- Song->Remove...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga R)
Removes the selected song from the library if in Browser view mode, or from the selected playlist (but not from the library) if in Playlists view mode.

   @{b}- Song->Add to Playlist->@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga 0...9)
This menu contains a sub menu item for each of the playlists currently in the library, viewable in the "Playlists" @{"view mode" Link "viewmodes"}. The first ten playlists will be assigned the keyboard shortcuts RAmiga+0 to RAmiga+9.The special @{"Shuffle" Link "shuffle"} playlist will always be the first in the list. Selecting one of the playlists in the submenu will add the selected song to the end of that playlist.

   @{b}- Playlist->New Playlist@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga N)
Creates a new playlist in the library named "Playlist N" where N is a number based on how many playlists already exist. The new playlist is empty by default, and can be renamed using the text gadget underneath the Playlists list in the Playlist view mode.

   @{b}- Playlist->Delete Playlist@{ub}
Deletes the currently selected playlist in the Playlists view mode. This action can't be undone, so be careful. This does not delete any songs from the library itself.

   @{b}- Playlist->Sort Playlist@{ub}
Not implemented yet - sorry!

   @{b}- Playlist->Shuffle@{ub}
This menu item contains several sub menu items for controlling the special @{"Shuffle" Link "shuffle"} playlist. Reshuffle clears the Shuffle playlist and fills it back up with the required number of tracks picked at random from the library. Selecting a menu item below this will set the Shuffle playlist to show that number of upcoming songs, i.e. 5, 10, 15 or 20, in the playlist. This setting will be saved along with other settings when the Save gadget is used in the Settings window.

   @{b}- Playlist->Import...@{ub}
This functions isn't implemented yet, and will possibly be removed in the future as it probably isn't of much use to a jukebox-oriented application like this.

   @{b}- Playlist->Export...@{ub}
This is a minimal function which will ask you to choose a filename, and then simply list the path of each song in the selected palylist as plain text. Might be useful for burning CDs etc...

   @{b}- Options->Sound...@{ub}
Still not sure if I'll implement this function. Originally thought of opening a window to control treble, bass, volume etc. but these functions all make things far more complicated, and I wouldn't use them myself anyway on the jukebox as it will be connected to an amplifier containing these controls...

   @{b}- Options->Settings...@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga G)
Opens the Settings window which lets you change various settings controlling how AmiTunes functions. See the @{"Settings page" Link "preferences"} for more information.

   @{b}- Options->Update Lists@{ub}  (Shortcut: RAmiga U)
Sort of a debugging option. This option rebuilds the Artists, Albums and Songs lists internally as under certain conditions they can become corrupted and show incorrect information. Try this item to fix any issues that might crop up, but please @{"let me know" Link "aboutme"} if you need to use this function regularly.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "preferences" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Preferences"

Options, Preferences and Settings in AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition

All the configuration options for AmiTunes can be accessed by selecting the Settings... menu item in the Options menu. Within this window the following options are available:

   @{b}- Library/Music Path@{ub}
This is the path where AmiTunes stores its library file, and also where it will store and control files when the appropriate other settings are active. See "Copy imported songs to AmiTunes drawer" and "Automatically sort AmiTunes librart drawer". This path must be set correctly for AmiTunes to work properly.

   @{b}- Player ARexx Port@{ub}
This is the name of the port to which AmiTunes will send its "engine" commands. Leave this set to "SIMPLEMHI" unless you're using a new engine with AmiTunes which requires a different name. Both the MHI MAS-Player engine and the ARexx-AmigaAmp wrapper engine supplied with AmiTunes use the "SIMPLEMHI" port name.

   @{b}- LCD Serial Device@{ub}
This is the name of the serial port device to use to display track information and menus on a serial LCD display. Unit 0 is assumed and cannot be changed. The serial port device is only opened if "Enable LCD Display" is enabled (see below). Use serial.device for a classic's internal serial port, or a1serial.device for an AmigaOne's first serial port.

   @{b}- Font@{ub}
Set the desired interface font here, using the full name (whatever.font), and set the size using the second gadget. Sorry, no fancy ASL requesters here, maybe in the future! This font is used for all parts of the interface, and is limited to 15 as the GUI isn't font sensitive. Yeah, I know, maybe in a future version! Note, changes to this setting do not take effect until the next time you start AmiTunes.

   @{b}- Decoding Engine@{ub}
Lets you select your desired MP3 decoding engine. Currently four options are available:
   - None (ARexx commands only): this does not load an engine, but simply issues the ARexx commands to the portname set above. Useful if you're developing an engine or running it separately, but probably not much use otherwise.
   - MAS Pro via MHI: This engine launches a small program called SimpleMHI, which is a small shell tool I wrote to listen for ARexx messages and act on them, sending the required files to the MAS Pro player via MHI. @{b}Important:@{ub} AmiTunes cannot tell if you have a MAS Pro attached to your Amiga. For safety, this option will not work if the OS is 4.0 or higher. However, starting the engine manually, or with a MAS Pro attached on a classic can lock up your machine in a nasty busy loop. Don't select it unless you have a MAS Pro attached!!
   - AmigaAmp via ARexx: Selecting this engine launches a simple ARexx wrapper which takes the SIMPLEMHI ARexx commands and redirects them to AmigaAmp, thus enabling software-only playback. Note, AmigaAmp must be running or this engine will simply quit.
   - Software: Selecting this option will use a basic decoding engine written specially for AmiTunes Jukebox edition to decode the MP3 using the CPU. This option has the advantage of not requiring AmigaAmp to be running as well, but is less flexible when it comes to audio modes etc.

Note, other MHI drivers are not supported with these options, but may be used if manually started. Also, this option takes effect when "Save" is clicked in the Settings window - if the option has been changed it will quit the running engine and try to start the newly selected engine. See @{"Engines" Link "engines"} for more details on the AmiTunes engine system.

   @{b}- Copy imported songs to AmiTunes drawer@{ub}
Enabling this option makes AmiTunes make a copy of any imported MP3s in the AmiTunes library drawer defined above, arranging them into drawers based on the ID3 tags contained in the file. It won't modify the original files in any way. Disabling this option means the files are added to the library from where they are, and AmiTunes won't attempt to rearrange them or anything.

   @{b}- Automatically sort AmiTunes library drawer@{ub}
This option tells AmiTunes you'd like it to update the library drawer whenever the properties of a file are modified. For example, changing the artist field of a song from "Damon Albarn" to "Blur" will cause AmiTunes to move the file from the "Damon Albarn" drawer into the "Blur" folder, creating it if it doesn't already exist. The same applies for album names. This option also enables the writing of ID3 tags, so modifying the artist, album, title, genre etc. will also modify the ID3 tags within the file for any other player to read. Disabling this option means the updated details are only saved in the library file, not back into the file, and also files won't be moved within the library drawer. Note, files stored outside the AmiTunes library folder will not be moved anywhere, regardless of this setting!

   @{b}- Auto-load library on startup@{ub}
Self explanatory really. This option makes AmiTunes look for and load its library file from the library drawer defined above as soon as it starts. I don't really know why you wouldn't enable this option, but if you do turn it off, the Project menu can be used to manually load the library.

   @{b}- Auto-save library on exit@{ub}
This option tells AmiTunes to save the library just before it quits. Normally this is a good thing as it saves any changes to the library (new files, removed files, modified playlists etc.), but it can take some time for very big libraries.

   @{b}- Enable LCD Display@{ub}
Enabling this option makes AmiTunes send information about the current song to the serial port in a format compatible with Crystalfontz 16x2 alphanumeric displays. On this screen it will display things like time of the current track, name/artist/album (user configurable via ARexx, keyboard or front panel buttons), as well as menus which can be navigated using ARexx, keyboard or front panel buttons, allowing the user to browse the library, add to and remove from playlists, change settings etc. without any TV or monitor display from the Amiga. For more information on this, see the @{"jukebox" Link "jukebox"} section.

As the LCD devices are dumb terminals (i.e., do not send any information or handshaking signals), using this option is safe without any LCD attached, though the serial device in question won't be available for any other apps wanting to use it.

   @{b}- Jukebox Mode@{ub}
This setting is mainly for using with all the jukebox hardware which I've added to my A1200 as part of my jukebox project. Basically, it suppresses (nearly) all requesters and makes decisions on your behalf so that AmiTunes can be used without any video display from the Amiga. Progress bars will be displayed on the LCD (if attached) instead of in a small window on the Workbench screen. Be careful, as this option will suppress the "Are you sure?" requesters when quitting without saving changes to the library, and other similar requesters.

   @{b}- Save and Cancel@{ub}
Pretty much do exactly what they say on the tin. There's no "Use" option, sorry about that! However, should you find yourself in a situation where AmiTunes doesn't work any more, you can restore the default settings by deleting or renaming the amitunes.prefs file in the program drawer. Most settings take effect when Save is pressed, but changes to Font settings won't take effect until you restart AmiTunes.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "addmusic" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Adding Music"

Adding Music to AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition

Songs can be very easily added to the AmiTunes library in a couple of ways, which are explained below. When a song is added to the library, first off its ID3 tags are scanned. Any information found will be added to the library entry associated with that file, and the Browser view mode lists will be updated to include the newly added file. Then, it is either copied to the AmiTunes library drawer or left where it is, based on the status of the "Copy imported songs to AmiTunes drawer" setting in the @{"preferences" Link "preferences"}. If the file is copied to the AmiTunes drawer, the original is left untouched, and the copy is placed in a folder based on the artist and album information from the ID3 tags. If some or all of the ID3 tags are missing from the file, the artist and album will be set to "Unknown" and the song title will be set to the filename where the tags are missing.

Additions to the library aren't automatically saved - you should save the library yourself using the Project->Save Library menu item, or set AmiTunes to automatically save the library on exit in the @{"preferences" Link "preferences"}.

   @{b}- Drag and Drop@{ub}
Dragging files from Workbench, DOpus 5 etc. and dropping them into the main AmiTunes window will automatically add them to the library if they're valid. several files can be added at once, but no progress bar will be shown if individual files are added in this way. Dragging drawers into the window will search the drawers for any valid files and add them to the library. If Jukemox mode is disabled, a requester will ask if you want to search the drawer recursively, in which case files all sub drawers will also be added to the library if valid. If Jukebox mode is enabled, recursive searching in sub drawers is chosen automatically.

   @{b}- Adding Single Files@{ub}
Using the Project->Import Song... menu item, you can choose a single file to add to the library via the standard file requester. This file will be checked, and if it's a valid MP3 it will be added to the library as described at the top of the page.

   @{b}- Adding a Drawer of Files@{ub}
Using the Project->Import Drawer... menu item, you can select a drawer containing MP3s for AmiTunes to search and import. All MP3s in the folder will be added, and if recursion is selected (see "Drag and Drop" above), all MP3s in sub drawers will be added as well.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "viewmodes" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - View Modes"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition View Modes

The main AmiTunes window can be set to one of two "view modes" - mainly due to the restricted space available on the native PAL screen I intended it to run on. At the top of the window a cycle gadget can be used to switch between the two view modes. "Browser" is the default mode with lists of artists, albums and songs, and gives you an overview of the entire library. More information about this view can be found in the @{"Main Window" Link "mainwindow"} section.

The "Playlists" view mode is similar to the "Browser" view mode, with all the same playing controls at the top of the window. The main difference is, instead of listing and editing lists of artists, albums and songs, the user has two lists. The left-hand list shows all the playlists currently in the library, and the right-hand list shows the songs contained in the currently selected playlist. Initially there will only be the special @{"Shuffle" Link "shuffle"} playlist in the Playlists list, but the user can add as many additional playlists as they like. Also, another special playlist will appear once a search has been carried out countaining the results of the most recent search. Playlists can be renamed by selecting them and editing the name in the string gadget below the list of playlists.

Songs will be listed in the right-hand list along with their artist and album as a single line of text. This is mainly to keep the list code simple, but it does look a little ugly when a proportional font is used due to the albums and artists not always lining up with each other. Choosing a fixed-width font in the @{"preferences" Link "preferences"} will eliminate this issue. Otherwise, this song list behaves the same as the Songs list in the Browser view mode - double-clicking them will play them, the Song menu carries out the same functions, etc. 

The Playlists viewmode includes a facility for changing the order of songs in the playlist. Simply select the song to move and use the buttons below the Songs list to move it up or down one position, or move it to the top or bottom of the playlist. The "X" button removes the selected song from the playlist (but not from the library).

Changes to the playlists are not automatically saved; saving the library either automatically on quitting, or by using the Project->Save Library menu item will save all playlists. Please note that playlists are limited to a maximum of 500 songs each.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "shuffle" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Shuffle Feature"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition Shuffle Feature

AmiTunes includes a special "Shuffle" playlist for playing random songs, loosely modelled on the old "Party Shuffle" playlist in Apple's iTunes. The first time this playlist is selected, it is populated with a number of random songs, and the first song is selected. As each song is finished, play moves onto the next song, and the finished song is removed. A new song is chosen at random and added to the end of the playlist to replace it, thus keeping the same number of songs in the playlist. This is a great alternative to the normal, basic shuffle function because upcoming songs are visible, and if the user doesn't like them, they can simply be removed from the playlist. Once removed, another random song is added to the end of the list to replace it. The order of upcoming songs can also be changed.

The number of songs in the playlist is chosen by selecting the appropriate sub menu item from the Playlist->Shuffle menu item. Songs that are added to the Shuffle playlist using the Song->Add to Playlist menu item will temporarily increase the number of entries, but as songs are removed this number will return to the chosen amount.

The Shuffle playlist is also stored separately from the main library (with the last played song information), as it changes far more often than the other playlists.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "arexx" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - ARexx"

ARexx and Amitunes - Jukebox Edition

AmiTunes opens an ARexx port named "AMITUNES" which can be used to control the basic functions of the software. And don't worry, the commands are not case sensitive! Currently supported commands are:

   @{b}- Quit@{ub}
Makes AmiTunes stop playing and quit, saving the library if configured to do so. A requester will be produced if Jukebox mode is disabled and unsaved modifications exist in the library.

   @{b}- Stop@{ub}
Stops playback.

   @{b}- Play@{ub}
Starts playback with the currently selected song. If AmiTunes is paused, playback will continue from where it was paused. If AmiTunes is stopped or playing a different song to the one selected, playback will start from the beginning of the selected song. If the currently selected song is already playing, nothing will happen.

   @{b}- Pause@{ub}
Pauses playback at the current position. If AmiTunes is already paused, this command will resume playback. Nothing happens if AmiTunes is currently stopped.

   @{b}- SkipFwd@{ub}
Skips onto the next track in the current track list. If repeat all is selected in the main window, skipping forward on the last track in the list will cause the first track to be played.

   @{b}- SkipBck@{ub}
Skips back to the previous track in the current track list. If repeat all is selected in the main window, skipping back on the first track in the list will cause AmiTunes to jump to the last track.

   @{b}- SeekFwd@{ub}
Seeks forward in the current track by a few seconds.

   @{b}- SeekBck@{ub}
Seeks backwards in the current track by a few seconds.

   @{b}- Enter@{ub}
Used to simulate pressing the "Enter" or confirm button on the front panel or keyboard. Intended for use with InfraRexx or similar in jukebox mode, so only really useful when used with an LCD.

   @{b}- Cancel@{ub}
Used to simulate pressing the "Cancel" or back button on the front panel or keyboard. Intended for use with InfraRexx or similar in jukebox mode, so only really useful when used with an LCD.

   @{b}- Info@{ub} [info_value]
Steps to the next piece of information to display on the LCD. When all eight types of information have been displayed, this command steps the display back to the first piece of information. The information which can be displayed is as follows:

   1) Song Title + Artist (default)
   2) Song Title
   3) Artist
   4) Album Title
   5) Length of song
   6) Genre of song
   7) Rating of song
   8) Total play counts for song

The optional argument @{i}info_value@{ui} can be used to jump directly to any piece of information. For example, the ARexx command 'Info 6' will display the genre of the current track on the LCD, regardless of what information was previously displayed.


AmiTunes also issues commands to an ARexx port ("SIMPLEMHI" by default) to control the decoding of the MP3 files. Usually the user wouldn't have to worry about them, but if you want to write or modify an engine, they might become useful. These commands are as follows:

   @{b}- OPEN@{ub} filename.s
Requests that the engine opens the supplied filename (given as an absolute path) and starts playing immediately. Cancels any pause or playback state.

   @{b}- PAUSE@{ub}
Toggles the pause state of the engine, i.e. if the engine is playing, pause playback. If the engine is paused, resume playback. Should be ignored if the engine is not playing.

   @{b}- STOP@{ub}
Asks the engine to immediately stop playback and cancels pause state if active. The MAS Pro driver will also empty its buffers at this point.

   @{b}- QUIT@{ub}
Immediately stop playback, free any resources allocated, and quit silently.

   @{b}- SEEK@{ub} bytes.l|seconds.l
Requests the engine to seek to the specified location in the current file. The SimpleMHI engine expects the argument in bytes, the ARexx dummy and software engines expect the argument to be given in seconds. AmiTunes will give the correct format of this argument based on the selected engine in the preferences. If no engine is selected, the argument will be given in seconds.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "engines" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Decoding Engines"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition Decoding Engines

The Jukebox Edition of AmiTunes uses a simple plug-in system for decoding MP3s, rather than decoding them itself. It does this by running the appropriate plug-in or "engine" as a separate task, and communicating with it via @{"ARexx" Link "arexx"}. AmiTunes can also be set to not run the engine but still issue the ARexx commands, which is useful for debugging or if you wanted to run an engine other than those supplied with AmiTunes.

There are three engines included with AmiTunes, and they can be selected in the @{"preferences" Link "preferences"} window. These are described below:

   @{b}- MHI@{ub}
The MHI engine is the original engine for use as part of the dedicated jukebox system, and uses an external MHI library for decoding the MP3 data. This allows various hardware decoders to be used without changing AmiTunes to support them, once they have the necessary MHI library file. Selecting "MAS Pro via MHI" in the settings of AmiTunes will start this engine configured to use a MAS Pro attached to the parallel port of your classic Amiga. @{b}PLEASE BE CAREFUL!@{ub} The MAS Pro driver cannot detect if a MAS player is attached, and will busy loop or crash if one isn't present. For safety, this option can't be enabled under OS4.

The engine can also be started manually if desired, and produces debug output which might help in troubleshooting. Also, if you have an MHI driver library for a decoder other than the MAS Pro, this can be used by starting it manually. To start it, open a shell window and navigate to the Engines drawer in the AmiTunes program drawer. Start the engine, giving the name of the desired library as an argument. For example, the default MAS Pro engine can be launched as follows:

1.Work:AmiTunes/Engines> SimpleMHI mhimaspro.library


   @{b}- AmigaAmp via ARexx@{ub}
The second engine supplied with AmiTunes is a simple ARexx wrapper which translates the engine messages to the ARexx port SIMPLEMHI to the AmigaAmp equivalents where required, and sends them to AmigaAmp, thus allowing for software decoding of MP3s with AmiTunes. This is really only of use on higher powered Amigas, and eventually won't be necessary when I complete the full version of AmiTunes, which will have internal decoding, support for more formats and a much better GUI. It doesn't take any arguments, and also produces some debug output when run from the shell. Start it from the Engines drawer with RX, for example:

1.Work:AmiTunes/Engines> RX SimpleMHI-Dummy.rexx


   @{b}- Software@{ub}
The third engine supplied with AmiTunes is a software only decoder written specially for AmiTunes Jukebox Edition. If selected it allows AmiTunes to be started as normal without having to have AmigaAmp running in the background. It will need a relatively powerful CPU to run, and will decode to AHI so this engine is only for those running a high-end classic or a "next gen", or those of you using WinUAE.

This engine uses AHI and normally requests unit 0, so if you need more flexibility about the sound outputs, it might be better to use AmigaAmp via ARexx as described above. However, if you start the engine manually from the shell, you can specify the unit number as an argument. If no unit number is specified, unit 0 is assumed. For example:

1.Work:AmiTunes/Engines> Software-Decoder 2


@ENDNODE
@NODE "files" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Program Files"

Files Used By AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition

AmiTunes uses three files to store various pieces of information which are required for it to function. These are described here. (You don't really need to know much about these files to use AmiTunes!)

   @{b}- amitunes.prefs@{ub}  (stored in the AmiTunes program drawer - PROGDIR:)
This is a binary file in which AmiTunes stores most of its settings. As it contains binary, it should not be edited by hand! However, if you find AmiTunes is crashing on startup, there might be something funny going on in here and simply deleting or renaming it will restore the default settings.

   @{b}- CurrentSong@{ub}  (Stored in the AmiTunes program drawer - PROGDIR:)
This is an ASCII file which is used to store information about the current song, so that if AmiTunes quits, it will remember the song it was playing last time and jump to it. It also contains the shuffle playlist and the current viewmode settings, so these will be remembered automatically as well.

   @{b}- Library@{ub}  (Stored in AmiTunes library drawer - Music:AmiTunes/ by default)
This file is used to store all the song information about every song imported into AmiTunes, as well as all the playlist information. It is partly human readable, so you can open it up and see tags like <song> and </song>, which mark the beginning and end of a song's information. Be careful if you edit this file as AmiTunes expects a very rigidly formatted file. It has some tolerance for errors in the file, but not much...

@ENDNODE
@NODE "keyboard" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Keyboard Control"

Keyboard Control of AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition

AmiTunes will also respond to keypresses on the keyboard if its window is active. These simulate the front panel buttons hardware so can be used in place of these buttons on machines without the required custom hardware, or indeed, non-classic systems. The keyboard shortcuts are as follows:

   - F1       Play
   - F2       Stop
   - F3       Pause
   - F5       Previous track
   - F6       Next track
   - R        Cycle repeat mode
   - I        Cycle information displayed
   - Delete   Remove song from playlist or library
   - Help     Opens this AmigaGuide. Note: linked files (history & pictures) won't work if the guide is opened in this way!
   - Space    Open song menu
   - Escape   Cancel / back
   - Enter    Enter / select
   - Up       Move up list / menu
   - Down     Move down list / menu

Descriptions are given with the @{"description of the front panel buttons" Link "jukebox"}. However, usage of the keyboard (and front buttons) really only makes sense when you're using an LCD display as all the navigation and settings are only shown on this display and not through the GUI.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "jukebox" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Jukebox Use"

Using AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition as a Jukebox

As AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition was originally intended to be used simply as the "brains" of an MP3 jukebox, here's how to use it as one. First, some custom hardware is required in the form of an @{"alphanumeric LCD display" Link "lcd"} for output, and @{"some buttons" Link "buttonshardware"} for input. With the LCD module attached and the option enabled in AmiTunes' settings, information can be displayed relating to the current song, the library can be browsed, playlists edited and settings modified, all without using, or even seeing, the GUI. With the custom buttons connected to the joystick port, AmiTunes can be controlled with the aid of the LCD screen, without the need for a mouse or keyboard. The front panel button functions are described below, and each button can also be simulated by a button on your Amiga's keyboard - just in case you don't have the button hardware - or a joystick port.

   @{b}- Play@{ub}  (keyboard: F1)
Plays the currently highlighted song, unless it's already playing. Resumes playback if paused.

   @{b}- Stop@{ub}  (keyboard: F2)
Stops playback, cancels pause state if paused.

   @{b}- Pause@{ub}  (keyboard: F3)
Pauses playback, or resumes playback if already paused. Has no effect if playback is stopped.

   @{b}- Skip Backwards@{ub}  (keyboard: F5)
Skips back to the previous track in the current track list. If repeat all is selected in the main window, skipping back on the first track in the list will cause AmiTunes to jump to the last track.

   @{b}- Skip Forwards@{ub}  (keyboard: F6)
Skips onto the next track in the current track list. If repeat all is selected in the main window, skipping forward on the last track in the list will cause the first track to be played.

   @{b}- Repeat@{ub}  (keyboard: R)
Cycles through AmiTunes' three repeat modes - "Off" (stops playing after the last track of the current track list), "Repeat one" (repeats the current track only", and "Repeat all" (repeats the entire current track list).

   @{b}- Info@{ub}  (keyboard: I)
Cycles through the eight different pieces of information to display on the LCD. When all eight have been displayed, this command steps the display back to the first piece of information. The information which can be displayed is as follows:

   1) Song Title + Artist (default)
   2) Song Title
   3) Artist
   4) Album Title
   5) Length of song
   6) Genre of song
   7) Rating of song
   8) Total play counts for song

   @{b}- Enter@{ub}  (keyboard: Enter)
Opens main menu and selects menu items.

   @{b}- Song@{ub}  (keyboard: Space)
Opens song-specific menu, for deleting, rating, adding to playlist etc.

   @{b}- Cancel@{ub}  (keyboard: Escape)
Cancels current menu and returns to parent menu. Exits from main menu back to information screen.

   @{b}- Up/Right@{ub}  (keyboard: Up arrow)
Moves to next item in current menu, or seeks forward in currently playing track if no menus are open.

   @{b}- Down/Left@{ub}  (keyboard: Down arrow)
Moves to previous item in current menu, or seeks backwards in currently playing track if no menus are open.


@{"Click here" Link "lcdmenus"} to read about the LCD menu system.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "lcdmenus" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - LCD Menus"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition LCD Menus

The menus are designed to be usable on a small 16x2 character LCD screen, and navigation is pretty easy. The top row shows the title of the current menu, and the bottom row shows the currently highlighted item. Opening the main menu will present a total of five options:

   @{b}- Artists@{ub}
Selecting this option will list all artists currently in your library. Selecting one of these will bring you to the Albums list (see below), but filtered to show only albums by the selected artist.

   @{b}- Albums@{ub}
Selecting this option lists all albums currently in your library, or albums by the selected artist if entered from the Artists list. Choosing one of these album titles will bring you to the Songs list (see below), but filtered to show only songs from the selected album.

   @{b}- Songs@{ub}
Selecting this option lists all songs currently in your library, or songs from the selected artist if entered from the Albums list, or songs from the selected playlist if entered from the Playlists list. Choosing one of these songs will start that song playing if it is not already.

   @{b}- Playlists@{ub}
Selecting this option lists all the playlists currently set up in your library. Choosing one of these playlists will bring you to the Songs list, showing the songs which are in the chosen playlist.

   @{b}- System Menu@{ub}
This item opens the @{"System Menu" Link "systemmenu"} which contains various options for controlling AmiTunes.

Pressing the Song Menu button while a song is playing, or highlighted in the Songs menu, opens the Song Menu which contains the following options:

   @{b}- Add to Playlist@{ub}
This option will present a list of the playlists in your current library. Choosing one of these playlists will add the selected song to that playlist.

   @{b}- Info@{ub}
This option presents a list of information relevant to the selected song including: title, artist, album, rating, file path etc. Pressing up/left and down/right will let you cycle through all available information.

   @{b}- Rate@{ub}
This option allows you to apply a rating to the currently selected song. Use up/left and down/right to adjust the rating from 1-5 hearts, or choose "None" to remove the rating.

   @{b}- Delete@{ub}
This option removes the song from the library, or just from the playlist if chosen while browsing a playlist. An "Are you sure?" message will be displayed - use up/left and down/right to choose yes or no.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "systemmenu" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - LCD System Menu

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition LCD System Menu

The System Menu contains special options for controlling AmiTunes. These are:

   @{b}- Settings@{ub}
Not implemented yet - sorry!

   @{b}- Import Songs@{ub}
This option provides three further options, corresponding to three locations in which AmiTunes can look for songs to import. The locations are hard-coded to CF0: (PCMCIA compact flash adaptor using cfd.device),  FTP Drawer (a drawer specially allocated in the AmiTunes library drawer called "_Import_"), and CD-ROM drive CD0: Selecting any of these locations will cause AmiTunes to search the drawer recursively for and MP3 files, copy them to the AmiTunes library drawer, arrange based on ID3 tags, and in the case of the FTP _Import_ location, delete the original files afterwards.

   @{b}- Save Library@{ub}
This option makes AmiTunes save its current library, ensuring all updates are kept. This is especially useful if the "Save library on exit" setting is not active, or if you don't exit AmiTunes before powering down.

   @{b}- About...@{ub}
Displays a list of information about AmiTunes. Use up/left and down/right to browse.

   @{b}- Quit AmiTunes (Shut Down System)@{ub}
This option gives you an "Are you sure?" choice before quitting AmiTunes, saving the library if that setting is active. To be safe, this option should be used before powering down the jukebox.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "lcd" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - LCD Hardware"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition and LCD Hardware

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition supports an RS-232 alphanumeric LCDs which follow the CrystalFontz protocol. I don't know if it's a widespread protocol, but I had a CrystalFontz display here, so that's what I used :) Please let me know if you discover that other LCDs work and I'll include them. Currently only a 16x2 character display is supported, but there are various styles of this display with different sized characters, different coloured backlights etc., and all these should work. You can order them from http://www.crystalfontz.com/ and I have to say, the quality and documentation provided is excellent! They also have drive bay mounting kits and much bigger displays with USB interfaces etc., but that's for another day...

Simply connect the serial port of your Amiga to the serial port of the CrystalFontz display using the straight through serial configuration, connect the power supply terminals to a +5V supply, and off you go! You can also send the serial in signal to the edge connector of the display if that suits better. Be sure to read the datasheets they provide on their website though!

@{"Example image of my prototype LCD" System "Multiview lcd.jpg"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "buttonshardware" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Front Panel Button Hardware"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition and Front Panel Buttons

To complete my stand-alone jukebox project, I decided to house the system in the shell of an old, dead CD deck. This also provided a bank of perfectly fitted buttons which were originally used to control the player. I decided to reuse these with my Amiga as inputs for controlling AmiTunes. As there were a total of 12 buttons on my player which were arranged in a 4x3 matrix, I was able to read all the buttons through one joystick port using a minimum of work. The 3 output lines were used to strobe the 3 x-lines, and the 4 remaining inputs used to read the 4 y-lines. A perfect fit! Unfortunately, some of the button labels didn't exactly match my needs, but I'll make do. The buttons with changed functions are as follows:

   - Open/Close: Cancel
   - Random: Song Menu
   - Program: Main Menu
   - Time: Info
   - Rewind: Up/Left (in menus)
   - Fast Forward: Down/Right (in menus)

@{"Schematic of button connections" System "Multiview buttons_schematic.gif"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "future" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Future"

The Future of AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition

Well, the jukebox edition of AmiTunes probably isn't going to go much further than where it is now, unless there's huge demand. Once it's finished I'll be working on the full-scale version of AmiTunes, a stand-alone library manager with a nicer GUI and more features for high-end Amigas. The only things I might do (again, unless there's huge demand for more additions) are:

   - Fix bugs
   - Add ASL requesters for paths and fonts in the preferences
   - Graphics for the control buttons instead of text
   - Icons for use under OS3

Feel free to @{"contact me" Link "aboutme"} though if you have any suggestions for this version of AmiTunes!
   
@ENDNODE
@NODE "bugs" "AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition - Bugs"

AmiTunes - Jukebox Edition Bugs

Hmmm... There are many, many bugs I'm sure, and many more I've squashed in the current version. Please @{"let me know" Link "aboutme"} if you find any, and I'll see about fixing them. No promises though :)

Known bugs:

   - Turning on jukebox mode when AmiTunes started with jukebox mode disabled causes the LCD menus not to clear back to the info screen. Solution: save the settings and restart AmiTunes.

@ENDNODE
